1st colonoscopy = ✅️ 
I'm glad to be starting my weekend knowing I'm cancer-free thanks to this routine procedure that honestly wasn't that bad. 🎉 Yes, maybe it was a little weird to be on an all liquid diet to prep for my procedure, but I wasn't hungry like I thought I would be) The procedure itself? Easy! An anesthesiologist put me right to sleep and all was done after a power nap! 😴 Since they didn't find any polyps, I don't need to repeat this for another 10 years. 🎉 And that first meal after the procedure is amazing! Swipe ⬅️ to see what my husband surprised me with when he picked me up. Spoiler: 🐠🌮So if you've been putting off a physical, mammogram, flu shot, COVID booster, or dreading your first colonoscopy, schedule these appointments because you owe it to yourself and your loved ones to stay in this world! ❤️ If you have questions about my experience, leave a comment or DM me. Let's talk about this to make it less scary and destigmatize the process! 
#friday #colonoscopy #coloncancer #health #screening #cancersucks

Gung Hay Fat Choy! Today is the start of the Lunar New Year which over 2 billion people around the world celebrate. 🎉  In our house, we say Gung Hay Fat Choy which means happy new year in Chinese. 🇨🇳
We've spent the days leading up to Year of the Rabbit 🐰 cleaning and tidying our house. Cleaning is forbidden in the first few days because it could sweep away good luck! 🧹 We also make sure our home is stocked with oranges because the gold color symbolizes wealth and prosperity. 🍊
Today, we started the new year by:
💃 Wearing red clothes (red is a lucky color)
🧧 Giving red envelopes (li see) to spread good luck and health, and to keep bad spirits away 
🥢Going out for dim sum at one of our favorite restaurants as our first meal because dumplings are lucky foods!
Whether or not you're celebrating today, I wish you and your family great health, happiness, and prosperity this year! 🧧🍊❤️
#lunarnewyear #chinesenewyear #gunghayfatchoy

Baking is my therapy and yesterday I made these don tarts after learning about the horrific tragedy in Monterey Park, California. 🥧 We had just come home from celebrating the start of the new year with dim sum at one of our favorite restaurants and the high I felt from enjoying a meal with my family immediately disappeared. 💔 I thought of the victims who passed away before their Year of the Rabbit could begin. The community, whose Lunar New Year celebrations were canceled because of gun violence along with their shattered sense of security, was also on my mind. 💔 What we're learning about the gunman does not diminish the tragedy and trauma felt by Asian communities in and around Monterey Park and around the country. This is very real for so many of us and especially hard at a time of year that should be filled with family and celebrations. 🧧🍊❤️
#lunarnewyear #montereypark #dimsum #Chinesenewyear #baking

Happy National Golden Retriever Day to Goldie! 🐶 Fun fact: We got Goldie from Lab Rescue because she had spent months at Golden Retriever Rescue. No one wanted her because she didn't look like a typical Golden. ☹️ She doesn't look like a typical Lab either but we're so glad she's ours! 🐾 We're especially glad to have our girl because last Friday she had to be taken to the emergency vet. 😳 We were at the beach and Goldie ran straight into the passenger door of a @ford F150, trying to cross the street to see a dog friend. 🛻 She limped to our yard, was in shock, and had a seizure. Her eye was swollen and blood was pouring from her mouth. We thought we were going to lose her. 😭 Fortunately she's ok! The vet commended her for being such a good girl and she got to come home the same night. Goldie has been taking it easy this week but has healed quickly. Swipe ⬅️ if you want to see her injuries after they were cleaned up by the vet. We're so very fortunate they weren't worse given the damage she did to the truck! ❤️
#nationalgoldenretrieverday #GoldenRetriever #Labrador #dogsofinstagram

Yesterday I made my debut on NBC News! 📺 April is Alcohol Responsibility Month and as part of my work as an Education Advisory Board Member for Responsibility.org, I shared how parents can talk about alcohol and underage drinking prevention. In case you missed the segment, here are some key points:
➡️ There’s no bad time to start the conversation. Kids ages 6-9 can understand the difference between things for adults and kids.
➡️ Talk early, talk often. Change the conversation as your kids get older and talk about how alcohol affects the developing brain.
➡️ Focus on facts. When kids have the facts, they can make better decisions and self advocate to feel comfortable saying no.
➡️ Honest conversations lead to you being a trusted adult who they can call or text when they feel unsafe, uncomfortable, or stuck. For more tips, visit @ask_listen_learn to find more conversation starters and @go_faar for resources that are helpful to keep the conversation with older kids in college. And swipe ⬅️ to see the funny faces captured by screenshots of the segment and some behind the scenes shots in studio. 😂
#alcoholresponsibilitymonth #nbc #nbcnewsnow #washingtondc #parenting

As a middle school computer science teacher, I taught a unit on AI to help my 8th graders realize the many ways AI is being used in our world. I always told my students they need to prepare for a world of work that doesn’t yet exist and certainly AI and robots are the future. 🤖

Tomorrow (Tuesday, April 18 3:30 PM ET / 12:30 PM PT) I'm excited to sit down with @embodiedinc Founder/CEO, Dr. Paolo Pirjanian for an IG Live to discuss how AI, technology, robots, and learning come together in Moxie, a robot designed for kids ages 5-10. 🤖

Join us as we talk about:
⭐️ The sophisticated technology in robots 
⭐️ What robots need to learn in order to provide care from humans
⭐️ Things your kids can do now if they're interested in AI, robots and/or computer science 
⭐️ If we might see more robots in our homes in the near future. I think we can all agree that a Rosie the Robot from the Jetsons, who cleans our house on a daily basis, would be pretty great! 🤖

What else do you want to know about AI and robots? Leave a comment below and I'll see you tomorrow for this awesome conversation! 🤖

#AI #robots #technology #learning #SEL #teachersofinstagram

Happy Derby Day! 🐎🌹🐎 To be honest, I didn’t know much about the Kentucky Derby before visiting Churchill Downs last summer. I knew it involved horse racing, the winning horse gets roses, and spectators sip mint juleps while wearing fantastic hats. 👒 I also remember the some of the words to Run for the Roses from learning it for an elementary school chorus concert! 🎵But to visit the museum and race track was pretty spectacular. I learned a lot about the history of the race that started in 1875 but was more interested in learning  about horses who do race in the Kentucky Derby like their lineage, what makes a good race horse, and how they’re trained and work with the jockeys who ride them. Have you ever been to Churchill Downs and are you a Kentucky Derby fan? If you are, enjoy sipping on mint juleps and watching the most exciting two seconds in sports! 🐎🌹🐎#kentuckyderby #derbyday #runfortheroses #churchilldowns #kentucky #travelky

In search of a place to connect with people I care about and meet new friends without spam or hate. Maybe this is it. 🎟️And yes, I know my data is a commodity but honestly, I’m already on this company’s other platforms so 🤷🏻‍♀️

Why do I take selfies? They help me monitor my eyes! 👀I have Graves’ disease and selfies are a good way to monitor any changes to my eyes that could be an indication of Thyroid Eye Disease (TED). Both Graves’ and TED are autoimmune diseases, but they require different doctors and treatments. 🩺 In honor of July being Graves’ Disease Awareness Month, I’m sharing the story of my diagnosis on the blog. Read how I knew something was wrong and why I’m vigilant about monitoring my symptoms, especially changes to my eyes. Link in bio. #Ad #GravesDisease #autoimmune #overactivethyroid

I came, I presented, I exhibited! 🎉 I’m back from 4 busy, yet inspiring, days in Atlanta at the American School Counselors Association’s annual conference where I got to speak to counselors from around the country with @mrbriancoleman and @ask_listen_learn. 🗣️I spoke about middle school brain development and why prevention education matters. 🧠The middle school brain is undergoing rapid development and changes so it’s important for our kids to know about the parts of their brains, what each does, and how these various parts are affected by alcohol. I’m proud of the work I do with educators to share Ask, Listen, Learn’s free prevention education curriculum because I know when kids understand the science and facts about what their brain does, how it works, and how it’s affected by alcohol, they’re more likely to make healthy decisions. 💕 #ASCA23 #dreambig #schoolcounselor #educator #AskListenLearn #healthychoices

Last February as my 8th graders were filing into the classroom, I felt my heart rate skyrocket as I waited for the bell to ring. 💗It was the first sign that something was wrong even though I felt fine otherwise. The following month I was diagnosed with an autoimmune disorder called Graves’ disease. 🩺Since July is Graves’ Disease Awareness Month, I’m sharing the story of my diagnosis on the blog to educate and help others. If you, or someone you know, is diagnosed with Graves’, they are at higher risk of developing Thyroid Eye Disease (TED), a separate but related autoimmune disease. 👀 To learn more about the symptoms of TED, common treatments, and to find a TED Eye Specialist near you, visit FOCUSonTED.com. #Ad #GravesDisease #autoimmune #overactivethyroid

What do you like to read? 📚My preference depends on my mood but cookbooks are always a favorite and I am beyond thrilled to add the World Central Cookbook to my collection! 💕 I got my signed copy last night before hearing @chefjoseandres speak with @mehdirhasan at Sixth & I and instantly fell in love! This cookbook is full of incredible recipes from around the world that I can’t wait to make for my family. It is also full of stories I’d the amazing people and communities who have benefitted from the incredible work @wckitchen does to provide fresh meals in humanitarian, climate, and community crises around the world. 🌎 I’ve always admired Chef Andres for being so quick to go to Haiti after the 2010 earthquake to provide what people really needed- food. The work he did in Haiti was the beginning of @wckitchen and a professional culinary school in Port au Prince. 🇭🇹During my many trips to Haiti, I fell in love with the people, culture, and food. I always hoped I would run into Chef Andres there but couldn’t be happier that his book includes recipes for dishes I love like griote, soup joumou, black beans, pikliz & more! 💕 Thank you, Chef, for your dedication to helping others by providing a very basic need to those when it is needed most. 🍛 Swipe to hear Chef Andres’ rapid fire answers to Mehdi’s questions, including which restaurant of his he likes better- @jaleobyjose or @zaytinya ! 😂 #joseandres #worldcentralkitchen #humanitarian #hero #washingtondc #cookbook #whatimreading

I’ve visited historic Old Town Alexandria many times but today I got to know a different side of the city by hearing little-known stories of Africans and African-Americans, both enslaved and freemen, and visiting historic sites. ⛪️ According to @j_chapman99 (founder of @manumissiontour, 4th generation Alexandrian, and Alexandria City Council Member!!) Alexandria, Virginia was one of early America’s main centers for the international and domestic slave trade. As we drove through different historic neighborhoods, the contributions by Black Americans were apparent throughout. 🏡 It was a powerful day and an excellent reminder that Black history IS Virginia history which makes it a huge part of American history! 🇺🇸 If you’re in the DC area or happen to be planning a visit to Alexandria, I highly recommend booking a tour with Manumission Tour Company to educate yourself about important historical events and individuals whose contributions to local history are just as significant as those usually mentioned in history books. 📚Huge thanks to John for making me aware of a very important part of Old Town Alexandria’s history and also to @toyotausa for inviting me to join be a part of their Steeped in History initiative. 🚘 #ToyotaPartner #ToyotaSteepedinHistory #alexandriava #blackhistory

And I boarded the plane
Touched down in the land of the Delta Blues
In the middle of the pouring rain 🎶  It is SO good to be back in Memphis! ❤️ Every year I think this might be my last race but the minute I get off the plane and start walking through the airport, I remember my why. My why becomes more apparent as I drive into downtown and past the @stjude campus where children and their families stay during their treatment for life threatening childhood illnesses which is free thanks to donors like you who ensure they never have to pay for treatment, housing, food, or travel. ✈️ At St. Jude kids get the best care, care that I could only hope for if my kids were to ever get sick. And that is my why. 🩺 On the St. Jude campus there are moms just like me who face the unimaginable every single day. I run for them so they can focus on helping their child live. ❤️‍🩹 I know if I was a mom of a patient, there would be an army of Heroes who would fundraise, train, and run for me and my sick child. I also run to give them hope which is something so many families have thanks to donors like you. St. Jude leads the way the world understands, treats and defeats childhood cancer and other life-threatening diseases. When this is your why, it’s hard to stop which is why I just keep going. ❤️#stjudeheroes #runforstjude #memphis #whyirun #nuunambassador

Fun fact: I’ve been to Haiti more times than any other country. 🇭🇹 Tonight my dear friend @explore_with_nat brought two of the metalwork artisans I’ve gotten to know through my trips to Washington, DC to share their craft and art at the US Embassy of the Republic of Haiti. ❤️ Seeing Nat, Serge Jolimeau, and Josnel Bruno brought back a flood of memories from past trips. ✈️ I have so many of their pieces in our home but tonight I couldn’t resist adding new ones to our collection. After the 2010 earthquake I visited Haiti for the first time and learned the best way to help Haiti is to support artisans by buying their work. This has not changed. Serge, Josnel, Rony Jacques, and so many more just want to continue the longstanding craft of making art out of recycled oils drums despite the war gangs have waged on the capital city of Port au Prince. Tonight it was a pleasure seeing old friends and introducing them and their craft to my husband who has heard me talk about how these pieces are made for years. I’m so glad he appreciates this art form as much as I do and can’t wait to find a place for our newest pieces in our home! 💕 If you’re local to the DC area, the holiday pop up shop at the Haitian Embassy is open over the weekend. Please stop by, say hi to Nat, and shop to support Haiti. 🙏🏼 #haiti #haitianart #haititourism #embassyofhaiti #washingtondc
